Use Codex internal web search for search queries. Do not use the configured browser or Playwright MCP to open public search-engine result pages. Use the configured browser only to open, interact with, and verify target source pages selected from internal search results, site navigation, saved evidence, or prompt context. All target source-page and source-data loading must go through the configured browser. Do not use non-browser loading mechanisms for target source data; direct HTTP, curl, requests, wget, and Python scraping are examples of forbidden replacements, not an exhaustive list.

Use browser_evaluate with pure browser JavaScript for page data extraction. Keep each evaluation small and single-purpose; use a block function with an explicit return instead of one dense nested expression when collecting structured data. The injected page JavaScript may read DOM, window, document, links, tables, visible text, and browser-visible state, then return serializable data. It must not use Node.js APIs or module systems: require, dynamic import, node: modules, fs, path, process, Buffer, and local filesystem access are forbidden in browser JavaScript. Do not use browser_run_code_unsafe.

Use browser_take_screenshot only when visible pixels or an image-backed source are required evidence. Write the capture under the current step's declared browser evidence directory, and use structured DOM extraction instead when it preserves the source data completely.

Before clicking an opener, inspect the current page state. If its target panel, dialog, or content is already open, inspect that target directly and do not click the opener again. Close or answer only unrelated browser-visible cookie banners, drawers, and overlays that intercept the intended action; never click a hidden DOM-only control. When a selector or text locator matches multiple elements, use the browser snapshot to choose a scoped unique target instead of repeating the broad locator.

Treat a connection-level browser navigation failure before a source response as recoverable, never as evidence that the source or requested content is absent. Keep the failure visible through browsing_error_list. Wait 5 seconds, call browser_close to discard the failed Chromium network context, then open the same target again; the next browser tool must create a fresh browser backend. If that navigation fails for the same transport reason, wait 10 seconds, call browser_close again, and open the same target one final time. These operations remain inside the current action attempt and must not restart the workflow step. Continue with source conclusions only after a response is available. If the final navigation still has no source response, report blocked browsing for that URL; do not convert the transport failure into a source-content rejection or absence claim.
